## 4. Sunlight & Shadow Conditions

Because New York City is located in the northern hemisphere, the southern side generally receives stronger and longer sunlight. The building’s massing is shaped so that the courtyard can receive more sunlight and open views compared with a conventional closed block.

The sloped roof and tetrahedral form reduce the height on one side and rise dramatically on the opposite corner. This strategy allows the building to create a large internal courtyard while still maintaining high residential density.

The courtyard receives light from above because the building does not form a fully enclosed vertical wall on all four sides. The sloped form opens the mass toward the sky and reduces the shadow impact on the internal garden.

Environmental implications include:

* The courtyard benefits from a more open sky condition.
* The sloped roof reduces the oppressive feeling of a closed perimeter block.
* Residential units can gain varied orientations and views.
* The tall corner maximizes density while the lower sloped edge improves light access.

