## 6. Design Implications

The site context suggests that VIA 57 West’s design strategy can be interpreted through four main ideas:

### 6.1 Combining tower density and courtyard living

The project responds to Manhattan’s high land value and density by stacking a large number of housing units vertically. At the same time, it introduces a courtyard typology to create shared open space within the block.

### 6.2 Creating a protected interior landscape

Because the site is near traffic infrastructure and dense urban conditions, the internal courtyard works as a protected communal space. It offers residents a green environment separated from the noise and scale of the surrounding city.

### 6.3 Opening the block toward light and views

The sloped massing opens the courtyard toward the sky and allows more sunlight to reach the garden. This helps avoid the darkness of a conventional enclosed courtyard block.

### 6.4 Responding to the Hudson River edge

The building’s location near the river gives it access to long views, light, and open space. The form takes advantage of this edge condition while still completing an urban block.

